name: Hydrogen
name_origin: composed of the Greek elements hydro- and -gen meaning 'water-forming'

name: Oxygen
name_origin: from the Greek oxy-, both 'sharp' and 'acid', and -gen, meaning 'acid-forming'

name: Sodium
name_origin: the English word soda (natrium in Latin)

name: Magnesium
name_origin: Magnesia, a district of Eastern Thessaly in Greece

name: Scandium
name_origin: Scandia, the Latin name for Scandinavia

name: Titanium
name_origin: Titans, the sons of the Earth goddess of Greek mythology

name: Vanadium
name_origin: Vanadis, an Old Norse name for the Scandinavian goddess Freyja

name: Manganese
name_origin: corrupted from magnesia negra, see Magnesium

name: Nickel
name_origin: from Swedish kopparnickel, containing the German word Nickel, 'goblin'

name: Gallium
name_origin: Gallia, the Latin name for France

name: Germanium
name_origin: Germania, the Latin name for Germany

name: Strontium
name_origin: Strontian, a small town in Scotland

name: Niobium
name_origin: Niobe, daughter of king Tantalus from Greek mythology

name: Ruthenium
name_origin: Ruthenia, the New Latin name for Russia

name: Palladium
name_origin: the then recently discovered asteroid Pallas, considered a planet at the time

name: Cadmium
name_origin: the New Latin cadmia, from King Kadmos

name: Antimony
name_origin: composed from the Greek anti, 'against', and monos, 'alone' (stibium in Latin)

name: Cerium
name_origin: the then recently discovered asteroid Ceres, considered a planet at the time

name: Praseodymium
name_origin: the Greek praseios didymos meaning 'green twin'

name: Neodymium
name_origin: the Greek neos didymos meaning 'new twin'

name: Promethium
name_origin: Prometheus of Greek mythology who stole fire from the Gods and gave it to humans

name: Samarium
name_origin: Samarskite, the name of the mineral from which it was first isolated

name: Gadolinium
name_origin: Johan Gadolin, chemist, physicist and mineralogist

name: Holmium
name_origin: Holmia, the New Latin name for Stockholm

name: Thulium
name_origin: Thule, the ancient name for Scandinavia

name: Lutetium
name_origin: Lutetia, the Latin name for Paris

name: Hafnium
name_origin: Hafnia, the New Latin name for Copenhagen

name: Tantalum
name_origin: King Tantalus, father of Niobe from Greek mythology

name: Tungsten
name_origin: the Swedish tung sten, 'heavy stone' (W is wolfram, the old name of the tungsten mineral wolframite)

name: Rhenium
name_origin: Rhenus, the Latin name for the river Rhine

name: Iridium
name_origin: Iris, the Greek goddess of the rainbow

name: Mercury
name_origin: the New Latin name mercurius, named after the Roman god (Hg from former name hydrargyrum, from Greek hydr-, 'water', and argyros, 'silver')

name: Polonium
name_origin: Polonia, the New Latin name for Poland

name: Radon
name_origin: From radium, as it was first detected as an emission from radium during radioactive decay

name: Francium
name_origin: Francia, the New Latin name for France

name: Thorium
name_origin: Thor, the Scandinavian god of thunder

name: Protactinium
name_origin: the Greek protos, 'first', and actinium, which is produced through the radioactive decay of protactinium

name: Uranium
name_origin: Uranus, the seventh planet in the Solar System

name: Neptunium
name_origin: Neptune, the eighth planet in the Solar System

name: Plutonium
name_origin: Pluto, a dwarf planet in the Solar System

name: Americium
name_origin: The Americas, as the element was first synthesized on the continent, by analogy with europium

name: Curium
name_origin: Pierre Curie, a physicist, and Marie Curie, a physicist and chemist, named after great scientists by analogy with gadolinium

name: Berkelium
name_origin: Berkeley, California, where the element was first synthesized, by analogy with terbium

name: Californium
name_origin: California, where the element was first synthesized

name: Nobelium
name_origin: Alfred Nobel, chemist, engineer, innovator, and armaments manufacturer

name: Hassium
name_origin: Hesse, Germany, where the element was first synthesized

name: Darmstadtium
name_origin: Darmstadt, Germany, where the element was first synthesized

name: Livermorium
name_origin: Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (in Livermore, California) which collaborated with JINR on its synthesis
